%p Derivational morphology is a very important class of word-formation dealing with the actual process of creating new lexical items. Whereas most of the morphology thus far discussed concerns taking existing words and modifying them by adding affixes to a stem, derivational morphology describes where these stems come from in the first place.
%p Throughout this section, affixes and other processes will be described as being either productive or unproductive. Productive processes are those which are still actively at work in the language, that could potentially be applied to many new roots and all speakers would immediately understand the novel meaning of the result. One of the most productive derivational affixes in modern English is -ness, which serves to nominalize an adjective. An unproductive process was likely once able to generate new words, but no longer can; it merely appears as a relic on a number of words, often with a somewhat unclear distribution across words and function. An English example might be -end, seen in words such as “reverend” and “dividend”, but which is virtually useless in terms of coining new expressions.

= section "Sources of New Words" do
  = section "Creation" do
    %p The most basic method of word creation is to create a new root from scratch. This is also one of the rarest methods, because new words are rarely made up without any prior base except for onomatopoeia: #{t "жиже", "źíźe"} “buzz”, #{t "яве", "iáve"} “woof”. These can then be put through the same internal derivation processes any other roots can, yielding related forms such as #{t "жижати", "źiźáti"} “buzz” and #{t "явати", "iávati"} “yap, chatter”.
    %p If the onomatopoeia happens to have an appropriate phonetic structure, part of the word can be reanalyzed as an ending, the most common examples being found in nursery words: #{t "мама", "máma"} “mother” and #{t "тата", "táta"} “father”, both of which have been reanalyzed as first declension nouns with the roots *мам- and *тат-.

  = section "Borrowing" do
    %p As the speakers of Novegradian travelled and came in contact with speakers of other languages, they frequently borrowed commonly-used vocabulary, technical terminology, local names for unknown items and new inventions, and local idioms. Some of the primary sources for new loans include Russian, Finnish, Komi, Swedish, French, German, and English.

    = section "Russian and Other Slavic Languages" do
      %p Of all the Slavic languages, Novegradian has had the most contact with Russian, and Russian still has significant usage in some parts of the Republic of Novegrad. When couplets appear, the Russian one usually has become more specialized in meaning, although it is not necessarily any more or less formal than the Novegradian equivalent. Common patterns in Russian loans is the pattern CoroC/ColoC/CereC/CeleC (where C represents any consonant) where Novegradian has CraC/ClaC/CreC/CleC, the use of Ё and Е where Novegradian and Е and Ѣ respectively, and the presence of historical palatalized consonants where Novegradian has none.
