      = render 'derivation_table', :headers => headers, :words => words
      %p A profession may be formed from a compound noun denoting some sort of field ending in the gerundive #{t "-нье", "-nje"} by simply dropping that ending. The feminine equivalent is formed by then adding -(и)ца.
      - words = [ [ { :cyr => "жемловѣденье", :lat => "źemlovědénje" },
                    "geology",
                    :arrow,
                    [ { :cyr => "жемловѣде", :lat => "źemlově́de" }, { :cyr => "жемловѣдица", :lat => "źemlově́dica" } ],
                    "geologist" ],
                  [ { :cyr => "нигопизанье", :lat => "nigopizánje" },
                    "bookwriting",
                    :arrow,
                    [ { :cyr => "нигописе", :lat => "nigopíse" }, { :cyr => "нигописца", :lat => "nigopísca" } ],
                    "bookwriter, author" ] ]
      = render 'derivation_table', :headers => headers, :words => words
      %p The suffix #{t "-(и)ца", "-(i)ca"} may be used to form a feminine noun from a masculine noun with no feminine equivalent, usually foreign borrowings: #{t "ауторе", "autóre"} “author” → #{t "ауторца", "autórca"}.
      %p Although not a native suffix, it should be noted that the agentive suffix #{t "-исте", "-iste"} forms its feminine counterpart with #{t "-иска", "-iska"}, the result of the simplification of an earlier *ист-ка: #{t "артисте", "artíste"} “(male) artist” → #{t "артиска", "artíska"} “female artist”.

    = section "Nouns from Other Nouns" do
      %p The suffixes #{t "-нике/-ника", "-nike/-nika"} can be used for inanimate objects as well, indicating something often used together with the base. -Нике is used when the base is masculine or neuter, and -ника if it is feminine.
      - headers = [ "Word", "Meaning", :arrow, "Noun", "Meaning" ]
      - words = [ [ { :cyr => "цае", :lat => "cáie" },
                    "tea",
                    :arrow,
                    { :cyr => "цайнике", :lat => "cáinike" },
                    "teapot" ],
                  [ { :cyr => "соли", :lat => "sóli" },
                    "salt",
                    :arrow,
                    { :cyr => "солника", :lat => "sólnika" },
                    "salt shaker" ],
                  [ { :cyr => "гажета", :lat => "gaźéta" },
                    "newspaper",
                    :arrow,
                    { :cyr => "гажетника", :lat => "gaźétnika" },
                    "newspaper rack" ],
                  [ { :cyr => "бенжине", :lat => "benźíne" },
                    "gasoline",
                    :arrow,
                    { :cyr => "бенжиннике", :lat => "benźínnike" },
                    "gas pump" ] ]
      = render 'derivation_table', :headers => headers, :words => words
      %p The suffix #{t "-ина", "-ina"} has a singulative function, used to create singular nouns from collective nouns or nouns that otherwise lack a singular. It is in origin the feminine counterpart to #{t "-ине", "-ine"}, as is seen in the #{t "-ѣнинe", "-ě́nine"} suffix denoting nationality described earlier. It is also used fairly productively to make singular nouns out of collectives with the #{t "-ия", "-ija"} suffix, though note the spelling.
      - words = [ [ { :cyr => "грахе", :lat => "gráhe" },
                    "peas",
                    :arrow,
                    { :cyr => "грашина", :lat => "gráśina" },
                    "pea" ],
                  [ { :cyr => "луди", :lat => "lúdi" },
                    "people",
                    :arrow,
                    { :cyr => "лудина", :lat => "lúdina" },
                    "human being" ],
                  [ { :cyr => "грозне", :lat => "grózne" },
                    "grapes",
                    :arrow,
                    { :cyr => "грознина", :lat => "gróznina" },
                    "grape" ],
                  [ { :cyr => "бѣлия", :lat => "bělijá" },
                    "sheets, linens",
                    :arrow,
                    { :cyr => "бѣлеина", :lat => "bě́ljina" },
                    "sheet, linen" ] ]
      = render 'derivation_table', :headers => headers, :words => words
      %p The suffix #{t "-(е)стуо", "-(e)stuo"} attached to a noun indicates “the state of being X” (cf. English -hood, -ship) or “the organization composed of X” (cf. -dom, -ment). If the noun ends in the agentive suffix #{t "-ителе", "-ítele"}, it is replaced by the suffix #{t "-я", "-ia"}. Mutations can occur.
      - words = [ [ { :cyr => "царе", :lat => "cáre" },
                    "tsar",
                    :arrow,
                    { :cyr => "царестуо", :lat => "cárestuo" },
