      = render 'derivation_table', :headers => headers, :words => words
      %p The last two of the above, страве and боғате, use the collective suffix to form a simple nominalization. These are historically compounds, the former related to дрѣво “tree” and the latter to боғе “God”.
      %p The suffixes #{t "-(о)те", "-(o)te"} (#{abbrev 'masc'}), #{t "-ата", "-ata"} (#{abbrev 'fem'}), and #{t "-ото", "-oto"} (#{abbrev 'neut'}) form nouns that display the quality of the adjective, both animate and inanimate. They are derived from the adjective modifying a declining form of the old demonstrative #{t "то", "to"} “that” that have since been reanalyzed as regular nouns: #{t "красноте", "krásnote"} “handsome man”, #{t "красната", "krásnata"} “beautiful woman”.

    = section "People from Verbs" do
      %p A person can be derived from a verb stem using the same sort of endings nouns use: -(е)це/-(и)ца and (less commonly) -аре/-ара, as well as the suffixes #{t "-теле/-делика", "-tele/-délika"} and the more colloquial #{t "-исе/-иска", "-ise/-iska"} (from Komi).
      - headers = [ "Word", "Meaning", :arrow, "Person", "Meaning" ]
      - words = [ [ { :cyr => "ледѣти", :lat => "ledě́ti" },
