      = render 'derivation_table', :headers => headers, :words => words
      %p There is a tendency, though not an absolute one, to stress any verbal prefixes, such as <i>о-</i> and <i>vo-</i> above.
      %p Resultatives are generally formed the same way, although can only be formed from perfective verbs. The endings theme vowel + #{t "-нье", "-nje"} or #{t "-ни", "-ni"} will sometimes be seen for collective resultatives, but are no longer productive.
      - words = [ [ { :cyr => "напизати", :lat => "napizáti" },
                    "write (#{abbrev 'pf'})",
                    :arrow,
                    { :cyr => "написе", :lat => "nápise" },
                    "letter, note" ],
                  [ { :cyr => "пойскати", :lat => "poiskáti" },
                    "search (#{abbrev 'pf'})",
                    :arrow,
                    { :cyr => "поиске", :lat => "pójiske" },
                    "search" ],
                  [ { :cyr => "содати", :lat => "sodáti" },
                    "give (#{abbrev 'pf'})",
                    :arrow,
                    { :cyr => "содани", :lat => "sódani" },
                    "tribute" ] ]
      = render 'derivation_table', :headers => headers, :words => words
      %p A few nominalizations are simply irregular: #{t "лубити", "lubíti"} “love” → #{t "лубова", "lubóva"} “love”<sup>2</sup>, #{t "пѣти", "pě́ti"} → #{t "пѣшне", "pě́śne"} “song”<sup>3</sup>, #{t "жити", "źíti"} “live” → #{t "житени", "źíteni"} “life”<sup>4</sup>.
      %p There are many suffixes used for turning a verb into an abstract noun. The most common is the gerundive #{t "-нье", "-nje"} (formed identically to the perfective participle, but with -нь- instead of -н-). Less common are #{t "-а", "-a"} and #{t "-ба", "-ba"}.
      - words = [ [ { :cyr => "цидати", :lat => "cidáti" },
                    "read",
                    :arrow,
