      = render 'derivation_table', :headers => headers, :words => words

    = section "Diminutives and Pejoratives" do
      %p Diminutives in Novegradian, as in other Slavic languages, are used very frequently. However, their formation can be quite complicated.
      %p The most basic suffixes are #{t "-ике", "-ike"} (#{abbrev 'masc'}), #{t "-ка", "-ka"} (#{abbrev 'fem'}), and #{t "-ко", "-ko"} (#{abbrev 'neut'}), preserving the original gender of the noun. These cause palatalization of the last consonant of the stem if it ends in a velar consonant, or lenition if it otherwise ends in a plosive. If the vowel preceding the feminine or neuter endings is /o/, it becomes /a/ in the diminutive.
      %p However, there are many alternative forms, to the point that any word can have multiple diminutive forms, sometimes even five or more. Frequent variants include doubling (#{t "-ишике, -ишка, -ишко", "-iśike, -iśka, -iśko"}) or even tripling (#{t "-ишицеке, -ишицка, -ишицко", "-iśiceke, -iśicka, -iśicko"}), an /n/ suffix (#{t "-ене, -ена, -ено", "-ene, -ena, -eno"}), an /sʲ/ (i#{t "-еше, -еша, -ешо", "-eśe, -eśa, eśo"}), other vowel variants (#{t "-еке, -оке", "-eke, -oke"}), and numerous combinations of the above.
      %p Pejoratives are easier to form, though still not entirely regular. They are created using the suffixes #{t "-охе/-оха", "-ohe/-oha"}, #{t "-ахе/-аха", "-ahe/-aha"}, and #{t "-ухе/-уха", "-uhe/-uha"}. The suffixes do not correspond to gender. When used with a noun that ends in -(е)це/-(и)ца, however, the pejorative must be placed before these agenitive suffixes.
      %p Note that these forms are distinct from those used for personal names, although there is some overlap.
    
    = section "Foreign Suffixes" do
      %p A number of foreign suffixes from Western European languages have entered Novegradian starting from around the 18th century, and have gained varying levels of productivity.
      %p The most productive foreign suffix is #{t "-аця", "-acia"} or #{t "-ася", "-asia"}, equivalent to English -tion. The former was the original form (borrowed from German or Polish) and the latter a later one (borrowed from Swedish and perhaps influenced by French), though colloquially more and more nouns in -аця are switching to -ася, which better fits Novegradian phonotactics. Along with -аця is #{t "-изме", "-izme"}, equivalent to English -ism.
      %p Less common suffixes include the agenitives #{t "-исте", "-iste"} (cf. English -ist), #{t "-оре", "-ore"} (cf. English -or), #{t "-аре", "-are"} (cf. English -arian), and #{t "-аже", "-aźe"} (cf. English -age, from French).
