  = section "Adjectivalization" do
    = section "Adjectives from Nouns" do
      %p The two most common adjective types in Novegradian are those formed with the #{t "-н-", "-n-"} suffix and those formed with the #{t "-ск-", "-sk-"} suffix.
      %p Н-suffix forms are usually relative (non-comparable), but can frequently be qualitative (comparable) as well. They generally mean ‘possessing the qualities of X’. This and other suffixes are added to the noun stem, adding an epenthetic vowel if needed, and then declined with normal adjective endings. The last consonant of the root is prone to mutation if it is a velar consonant.
      - headers = [ "Word", "Meaning", :arrow, "Adjective", "Meaning" ]
      - words = [ [ { :cyr => "велке", :lat => "vélke" },
                    "wolf",
                    :arrow,
                    { :cyr => "велцене", :lat => "vélcene" },
                    "lupine" ],
                  [ { :cyr => "дрѣво", :lat => "drě́vo" },
                    "tree, wood",
                    :arrow,
                    { :cyr => "дрѣвне", :lat => "drě́vne" },
                    "wooden" ],
                  [ { :cyr => "боғе", :lat => "bóğe" },
                    "god",
                    :arrow,
                    { :cyr => "божне", :lat => "bóźne" },
                    "god(like)" ],
                  [ { :cyr => "граде", :lat => "gráde" },
                    "city",
                    :arrow,
                    { :cyr => "градне", :lat => "grádne" },
                    "urban" ],
                  [ { :cyr => "стаље", :lat => "stáłe" },
                    "steel",
                    :arrow,
                    { :cyr => "стаљне", :lat => "stáłne" },
                    "steel" ],
                  [ { :cyr => "нокьи", :lat => "nókji" },
                    "night",
                    :arrow,
                    { :cyr => "нокне", :lat => "nókne" },
                    "night(time),<br>nocturnal" ] ]
      = render 'derivation_table', :headers => headers, :words => words
      %p The behavior of root-final /c/ before the adjectival -н- is somewhat complex. If it derives from an historical *kt, it becomes /k/: #{t "нокьи", "nókji"} “night” (Common Slavic *noktь) → #{t "нокне", "nókne"} “night(time)”. If it derives from an historical *tj, it becomes /t/: #{t "тишикьа", "tíśikja"} “thousand” (Common Slavic *tysętja) → #{t "тишитне", "tíśitne"} “thousandth”. Root-final /ɟ/ always becomes /d/ since it always falls into this second class. The palatal fricatives /ç/ and /ʝ/ are unaffected, however.
      %p Ск-suffix forms are almost always relative, and are used most often to turn a place name into an adjective. This is the most productive form of adjective derivation.
      - words = [ [ { :cyr => "Новеграде", :lat => "Novegráde" },
                    "Novegrad",
                    :arrow,
                    { :cyr => "новеградеске", :lat => "novegrádeske" },
                    "Novegradian" ],
                  [ { :cyr => "Германя", :lat => "Germánia" },
                    "Germany",
                    :arrow,
                    { :cyr => "германеске", :lat => "germáneske" },
                    "German" ],
                  [ { :cyr => "Кидае", :lat => "Kidáie" },
                    "China",
                    :arrow,
                    { :cyr => "кидайске", :lat => "kidáiske" },
                    "Chinese" ],
                  [ { :cyr => "Англия", :lat => "Ánglija" },
                    "England",
                    :arrow,
                    { :cyr => "английске", :lat => "английске" },
                    "English" ],
                  [ { :cyr => "Нева", :lat => "Nevá" },
                    "Nevá (river)",
                    :arrow,
                    { :cyr => "неуске", :lat => "néuske" },
                    "of the Nevá" ] ]
      = render 'derivation_table', :headers => headers, :words => words
      %p The definite suffixes <i>-skei</i>/<i>-skoie</i>/<i>-skaia</i> are often used in place names.
      %p It is not always predictable what will happen to the final consonant or vowel of a noun when the -ск- suffix is added. This is highly dependent on both the ending of the noun and when the adjective form first appeared in the language.
      %p For first declension nouns, there are two options. Most commonly, /e/ is inserted between the root and the suffix, with no palatalization: #{t "Вољга", "Vółga"} “Volga” → #{t "вољгеске", "vółgeske"}. Many other nouns, however, use the older suffix <i>-ine-</i>, again with no palatalization: #{t "Вишера", "Víśera"} “Víśera” → #{t "вишеринеске", "viśeríneske"}. This form is most common for adjectivalizing local place names. For this reason, overuse of <i>-ine-</i> tends to sound “rustic”.
      %p Second declension nouns, however, almost universally use <i>-ine-</i>: #{t "Вагря", "Vágria"} “Hungary” → #{t "огринеске", "ogríneske"}. Apparent exceptions, such as #{t "сумеске", "súmeske"} for “Finnish” when “Finland” is #{t "Сумя", "Súmia"}, are usually not directly related. In this case, the example is derived from an older name for Finland, #{t "Суме", "Súme"}.
      %p Third and fourth declension nouns can basically be divided into three phases, based on when the adjective first came into use. The oldest words (roughly prior to 1100 AD) generally add /e/ to the root and show no palatalization: #{t "Новеграде", "Novegráde"} “Novegrad” → #{t "новеградеске", "novegrádeske"}. Middle period nouns (roughly 1100 to 1800) use the /e/ suffix as well, but the root ends in /t d k g x/, they will generally palatalize: #{t "Цахя", "Cáhia"} “Czech [Republic]” → #{t "цашеске", "cáśeske"}. This is largely due to Russian and Church Slavonic influence. New period nouns (roughly post 1800) have returned to the original system of /e/ without palatalization: #{t "Ираке", "Iráke"} “Iraq” → #{t "иракеске", "irákeske"}.
      %p Fifth declension nouns almost always use the /e/ suffix without palatalization: #{t "Дони", "Dóni"} “Denmark” → #{t "донеске", "dóneske"}. However, sometimes the connecting suffix is /i/, but this is rare and usually a regionalism.
      %p There are no sixth declension nouns that take the -ск- suffix.
      %p However, there are certain root-final consonants that trigger exceptions to the above rules, no matter the declension of the noun:
      %ul
        %li /j/: Roots ending in /j/ have no connecting morpheme between the root and the -ск- suffix: #{t "Кидае", "Kidáie"} “China” → #{t "кидайске", "kidáiske"}.
        %li /ij/: Roots ending in /ij/ follow the same rule as above, but orthographic -ий- is usually just pronounced /i/ (or colloquially, /aj/): #{t "Англия", "Ánglija"} → #{t "английске", "anglíjske"}.
        %li /β/: Root-final /β/ almost always reduces to /w/ with no connecting morpheme: #{t "Нева", "Nevá"} → #{t "неуске", "néuske"}.
        %li /s/: Roots ending in /s/ generally have no connecting morpheme. Orthographic -сс- is pronounced simply as /s/: #{t "Пруся", "Prúsia"} “Prussia” → #{t "прусске", "prússke"}. There is some variation here, however: second declension nouns whose roots end in /s/ sometimes may still take <i>-ine-</i> (and #{t "прузинеске", "pruzíneske"} for “Prussian” may be seen in a number of place names).
      %p A small set of nouns can take an adjective ending without any suffix (e.g., #{t "злато", "zláto"} “gold” → #{t "злате", "zláte"} “golden”), but this is relatively uncommon unless there is some sort of prefix involved as well.
      %p The endings #{t "-ов-", "-ov-"} and #{t "-оу-н-", "-oun-"}, derived from the old genitive ending still seen in the partitive plural, form relative adjectives (cf. English -ic, -al). Note that fourth declension bases will generally take #{t "-ев-", "-ev-"} and #{t "-еу-н-", "-eun-"} instead.
      %p #{t "-ив-", "-iv-"} forms qualitative adjectives, and carries roughly the same meaning as English -ful. #{t "-аљ-н-", "-ałn-"} (from English -al) is generally only found in loanwords. #{t "-ице-ск-", "-icesk-"} and the reduced form #{t "-е-ск-", "-esk-"} are used when the root ends in /s z ts dz/ derive from a combination of English -ic with the Slavic <i>-sk-</i>, but have since spread to almost any abstract noun ending in -(и)я by analogy, even if the English equivalent never had -ic (e.g., “information” below).
      - words = [ [ { :cyr => "лизике", :lat => "lizíke" },
                    "language",
                    :arrow,
                    { :cyr => "лизикеве", :lat => "lizíkeve" },
                    "linguistic" ],
                  [ { :cyr => "небесо", :lat => "nébeso" },
                    "sky",
                    :arrow,
                    { :cyr => "небезоуне", :lat => "nebezóune" },
                    "celestial" ],
                  [ { :cyr => "вѣра", :lat => "vě́ra" },
                    "faith",
                    :arrow,
                    { :cyr => "вѣриве", :lat => "věríve" },
                    "faithful" ],
                  [ { :cyr => "сцестия", :lat => "scestijá" },
                    "luck",
                    :arrow,
                    { :cyr => "сцестиве", :lat => "scéstive" },
                    "lucky" ],
                  [ { :cyr => "центре", :lat => "céntre" },
                    "center",
                    :arrow,
                    { :cyr => "центраљне", :lat => "centráłne" },
                    "central" ],
                  [ { :cyr => "хедерася", :lat => "hederásia" },
                    "federation",
                    :arrow,
                    { :cyr => "хедераљне", :lat => "hederáłne" },
                    "federal" ],
                  [ { :cyr => "исторя", :lat => "istória" },
                    "history",
                    :arrow,
                    { :cyr => "историцеске", :lat => "istoríceske" },
                    "historical" ],
                  [ { :cyr => "инвормася", :lat => "invormásia" },
                    "information",
                    :arrow,
                    { :cyr => "инвормасеске", :lat => "invormáseske" },
                    "informational" ] ]
      = render 'derivation_table', :headers => headers, :words => words
      %p The suffix #{t "-ив-", "-iv-"} is also used productively to derive adjectives from abstract nominals that end in -ости: #{t "милости", "mílosti"} “mercy” → #{t "милостиве", "milóstive"} “merciful, gracious”.
      %p The suffix #{t "-ист-", "-íst-"} means “full of”, but more literally than -ив-. It is somewhat literary, however, having been more or less completely replaced by the prefix #{t "много-", "mnogo-"}, described later: #{t "гора", "góra"} “mountain” → #{t "гористе", "goríste"} “mountainous”.
      %p The suffixes #{t "-ат-", "-át-"} and #{t "-овит-", "-ovit-"} are a non-productive means of making adjectives out of concrete nominals. They are only found on a handful of words, such as #{t "роге", "róge"} “horn” → #{t "рогате", "rogáte"} “horned”, or #{t "плоде", "plóde"} “fruit, offspring” → #{t "плодовите", "plodovíte"} “fruitful, currently producing a great quantity of fruit”.
      %p The suffix #{t "-оват-", "-ovát-"} weakens an adjective, meaning “rather X” or “X-ish”: #{t "шинье", "śínje"} “blue” → #{t "шиньовате", "śinjováte"} “bluish”.
      %p The suffix #{t "-осн-", "-osn-"}, of Komi origin, means “covered/coated/spattered with X”: #{t "крев", "krév"} “blood” → #{t "кревосне", "krevósne"} “blood-spattered”, #{t "цервене", "cérvene"} “red” → #{t "цервеносне", "cervenósne"} “spotty red”.
      %p The suffix #{t "-ѣн-", "-ěn-"} means “made of”, and is attached to bases of various materials: #{t "лене", "léne"} “flax” → #{t "ленѣне", "léněne"} “linen”, #{t "мѣди", "mě́di"} “copper (noun)” → #{t "мѣдѣне", "mě́děne"} “copper (#{abbrev 'adj'})”.
      %p The suffix #{t "-ушн-", "-uśn-"} is a pejorative, forming adjectives with negative connotations from nouns. It is historically related to the nominal pejorative suffix -ух-, but can be applied to nouns that never take this suffix as well: #{t "клапе", "klápe"} “boy” → #{t "клапушне", "hlapúśne"} “boyish”, #{t "дѣвушка", "dě́vuśka"} “girl” → #{t "дѣвушне", "děvúśne"} “girlish”, #{t "старце", "stárce"} “old man” → #{t "старушне", "starúśne"} “senile”, #{t "суиньа", "suínja"} “wild pig” → #{t "суиньушне", "suinjúśne"} “piggish”.
      %p The prefix #{t "бес-", "bes-"} means “without”, much like the English suffix -less. Note that when it is added to adjectives with the <i>-n-</i> suffix, they generally tend to switch to the <i>-ov-</i>/<i>-ev-</i> suffix: #{t "соунце", "sóunce"} “sun” → #{t "солнецне", "solnécne"} “sunny” → #{t "бессоунцеве", "bessóunceve"} “sunless”; #{t "вѣтре", "vě́tre"} “wind” → #{t "вѣтрене", "vě́trene"} “windy” → #{t "бесвѣтреве", "besvě́treve"} “windless”.
      %p Many animals have two adjective forms, although their meanings are identical. The adjective endings are allowed to be added directly onto the root of the animal with a <i>-j-</i> intermediary (which is frequently absorbed by the consonant before it), so that both j-suffix and n-suffix animal terms will be seen. The former were originally descended from true possessive adjectives, which have largely been lost as a productive force in Novegradian. Quite a few have become extremely irregular, such as тоце “avian” below (from Common Slavic *pъtъk-j-ъ). The j-suffix forms are increasingly rare outside of technical fields such as taxonomy or biology.
      - words = [ [ { :cyr => "велке", :lat => "vélke" },
                    "wolf",
                    :arrow,
                    [ { :cyr => "велцене", :lat => "vélcene" }, { :cyr => "велце", :lat => "vélce" } ],
                    "lupine, wolf’s" ],
                  [ { :cyr => "каля", :lat => "kália" },
                    "fish",
                    :arrow,
                    [ { :cyr => "калиене", :lat => "káliene" }, { :cyr => "калие", :lat => "kálie" } ],
                    "piscine, fish’s" ],
                  [ { :cyr => "коша", :lat => "kóśa" },
                    "cat",
                    :arrow,
                    [ { :cyr => "кошне", :lat => "kóśne" }, { :cyr => "кошие", :lat => "kóśie" } ],
                    "feline, cat’s" ],
                  [ { :cyr => "поска", :lat => "póska" }, 
                    "bird",
                    :arrow,
                    [ { :cyr => "посцене", :lat => "póscene" }, { :cyr => "тоце", :lat => "tóce" } ],
                    "avian, bird’s" ] ]
      = render 'derivation_table', :headers => headers, :words => words

    = section "Adjectives from Verbs" do
      %p Adjectives can be derived from verbs, but generally not without the help of some sort of adjectival prefix. The verb root is isolated, the prefix added, and then this stem is otherwise treated as though it were a noun, using the same sort of endings (-ов-, -ив-, -н-). See the “Noun and Adjective Prefixes” section below for more information. The three verbal participles are also used to modify nouns, and do not require any sort of additional prefixes.
      %p There is one exception, however, known as the “necessitive participle”, though despite the name it is generally not viewed as a true participle by Indo-Europeanists. It is formed by adding the suffix #{t "-телне", "-telne"} to the infinitive stem. If the infinitive stem ends in /t d s z k g/ (i.e., the infinitive ends in #{t "-сти", "-sti"} or #{t "-йкьи", "-ikji"}), then the suffix #{t "-ителне", "-ítelne"} is used, with palatalization of /k g/ to /ts dz/. These adjectives have the meaning “that must be Xed” for transitive verbs and “that must X” for intransitive verbs:
      %ul
        %li #{t "рѣѕити", "rědzíti"} “say” → #{t "рѣѕителне", "rědzítelne"} “that must be said”
        %li #{t "видѣти", "víděti"} “see” → #{t "видѣтелне", "vidě́telne"} “that must be seen”
        %li #{t "жити", "źíti"} “live” → #{t "жителне", "źítelne"} “that must live”
        %li #{t "плайкьи", "pláikji"} “cry” → #{t "плацителне", "placítelne"} “that must cry”
        %li #{t "класти", "klásti"} “bury” → #{t "кладителне", "kladítelne"} “that must be buried”
        %li #{t "исти", "ísti"} “go” → #{t "идителне", "idítelne"} “that must go”
      %p When negated with the prefix #{t "не-", "ne-"}, the necessitive participle indicates improperness or impossibility:
      %ul
        %li
          = t("нерѣѕителне", "nerědzítelne")
          “that must not be said”
        %li
          = t("невидѣтелне", "nevidě́telne")
          “that must not be seen”
        %li
          = t("нежителне", "neźítelne")
          “that must not live”
        %li
          = t("неплацителне", "neplacítelne")
          “that must not cry”
        %li
          = t("некладителне", "nekladítelne")
          “that must not be buried”
        %li
          = t("неидителне", "nejidítelne")
          “that must not go” 
      %p The passive imperfective participle also has one additional idiomatic function. It can indicate possibility, much like the English suffix -able/-ible: #{t "видиме", "vidíme"} “visible”, #{t "дадоме", "dádome"} “givable”, etc.

    = section "Adjective Diminutives" do
      %p Diminutive forms of adjectives also exist, which generally imply a sense of closeness or ‘cuteness’, and so are particularly common when speaking with children, or when modifying affectionately diminutive nouns. They are formed using the suffixes #{t "-енк-", "-enk-"}, #{t "-инк-", "-ink-"}, #{t "-еник-", "-enik-"}, and #{t "-иник-", "-inik-"} attached to an adjectival stem. These diminutives cannot be used with adjectives already containing the suffixes <i>-n-</i> or <i>-sk-</i>, but are otherwise quite productive. Sometimes other suffixes are dropped when diminutive endings are added, as in слазке below.
      %p Some example diminutives:
      - headers = [ "Word", "Meaning", :arrow, "Diminutive", "Meaning" ]
      - words = [ [ { :cyr => "добре", :lat => "dóbre" },
                    "good",
                    :arrow,
                    { :cyr => "добренке", :lat => "dóbrenke" },
                    "good" ],
                  [ { :cyr => "слазке", :lat => "slázke" },
                    "sweet",
                    :arrow,
                    { :cyr => "сладинке", :lat => "sládinke" },
                    "sweet" ],
                  [ { :cyr => "тољсте", :lat => "tółste" },
                    "fat",
                    :arrow,
                    { :cyr => "тољстинике", :lat => "tołstiníke" },
                    "chubby" ] ]
      = render 'derivation_table', :headers => headers, :words => words

    = section "Complex Adjectives" do
      %p Novegradian makes use of a small set of “complex adjectives”, two adjectives modifying a single noun that both decline, but are written as a single hyphenated word without any sort of conjunction, that take on new meanings separate from those of the two adjectives forming them. These include #{t "старе-младе", "stáre-mláde"} “of all ages” (lit. “old-young”), #{t "диляне-краске", "diliáne-kráske"} “of uneven length” (lit. “long-short”), #{t "шинье-цервене", "śínje-cérvene"} “multicolored, motley” (lit. “blue-red”). The two adjectives composing each complex adjective are opposites or near-opposites, and the new form represents a variation everywhere in between the two.

  = section "Verbalization" do
    %p Any part of speech can generally be converted into a verb by taking the root and treating that as a verbal root, then assigning it a conjugation class, theme vowel, etc. The first and second conjugations are used for most such derivations, although the third is occasionally seen as well. If the root is in the second or third conjugation and ends in a consonant prone to mutation, that consonant will likely mutate due to analogy with other verbs, even if the root is foreign. For this reason, many foreign roots end up in the non-mutating first conjugation.
    - headers = [ "Word", "Meaning", :arrow, "Verb", "Meaning" ]
    - words = [ [ { :cyr => "каля", :lat => "kália" },
