    t%p There are a few general tendencies that can be noted regarding the conjugations that derived verbs are placed in. The second conjugation (with <i>-i-</i> as the infinitive thematic vowel), for example, tends to indicate some sort of transformation or causation (as in #{t "сухе", "súhe"} “dry” → #{t "сушити", "súśiti"} “dry, make dry”). The third conjugation ending #{t "-нати", "-nati"}, known as a ‘punctual’, marks a single instanteous action, especially physical ones, such as #{t "крикнати", "kriknáti"} “shout (#{abbrev 'pf'})” and #{t "метнати", "metnáti"} “hurl, strike (#{abbrev 'pf'})”. Nearly all verbs ending in -нати are perfective, since after all a single instantaneous action can’t be progressive or prolonged.
    %p There are also a few pairs of verbs affixes (namely <i>-i-</i>/<i>-na-</i> and <i>-i-</i>/<i>-ě-</i>) worth noting that no longer have productive force, but nevertheless are prominant.
    %p A number of transitive second conjugation verbs (i.e., having the suffix <i>-i-</i> in the infinitive) have intransitive counterparts with <i>-na-</i>: #{t "гашити", "gáśiti"} “extinguish, put out [a flame, etc.]”, #{t "гаснати", "gasnáti"} “go out”; #{t "меражити", "meráźiti"} “freeze (#{abbrev 'tr'})”, #{t "морзнати", "morznáti"} “freeze (#{abbrev 'intr'}), go numb”; #{t "миғцити", "miğcíti"} “soften (#{abbrev 'tr'})”, #{t "миғнати", "miğnáti"} “soften (#{abbrev 'intr'}), get soft”.
    %p Several causative verbs in <i>-i-</i> also have stative counterparts in <i>-ě-</i> (third conjugation). This is especially common with adjective bases: #{t "шиньити", "śinjíti"} “make blue”, #{t "шиньѣти", "śinjě́ti"} “appear blue”, #{t "желенити", "źeleníti"} “make green”, #{t "желенѣти", "źeleně́ti"} “appear green, be envious”.
    %p Although these patterns are no longer productive, they have had sporadic influence on other verbs as a result of analogy. For example, the former relationship has been applied to the verb #{t "омѣти", "omě́ti"} “know how to” to create the new verb #{t "омити", "omíti"} “teach how to”.

  = section "Adverbialization" do
