= section "Prefixial Derivation" do
  = section "Noun and Adjective Prefixes" do
    %p The following prefixes are attached directly onto a noun or adjective to change the meaning, in much the same way noun and adjective prefixes work in English. Many adjectivalizations require some sort of prefix related to the meaning—for example, #{t "приглубе", "priglúbe"} “deep” requires the prefix при-, meaning “touching” or “close to”, the intention here being “close to the bottom”; *глубе alone has no meaning. Similarly, the prefixless *видеце (from “see” and the agentive suffix) is meaningless, but with a prefix, #{t "безвидеце", "bezvídece"} becomes “blind man” (without-see-#{abbrev 'agent'}). All of these prefixes are highly productive.
    %p It should be noted that there is a great deal of overlap between substantive and verbal prefixes, with many identical forms, although often different meanings. The distinction between the two is further confused  by the ability of prefixed verbs to form derived nouns and adjectives that still bear a verbal prefix. For this reason, this section will avoid deverbal forms as much as possible.

    = section "Без-" do
      %p The most basic sense of без- is “without”, corresponding roughly with English -less. Before voiceless consonants, it takes the form #{t "бес-", "bes-"}. With adjectives, it generally forces the suffix -ов-/-ев-. Abstract nouns will usually acquire the collective suffix -ия unless another abstract marker (e.g., -ости) is present.
      %p It can be added to a small set of primitive nouns referring to body parts to form adjectives without need of a suffix, as in безроке below.
      %p Examples:
      %ul
        %li #{t "безвидеце", "bezvídece"} “blind man” (← #{t "видѣти", "víděti"} “see”)
        %li #{t "безнадѣгьове", "beznadě́gjove"} “hopeless” (← #{t "надѣгьа", "nadě́gja"} “hope”)
        %li #{t "бесшилия", "besśilijá"} “weakness” (← #{t "шила", "śíla"} “strength”)
        %li #{t "бескараљности", "beskaráłnosti"} “impunity” (← #{t "караљне", "karáłne"} “punishable”)
        %li #{t "безроке", "bezróke"} “armless” (← #{t "рока", "róka"} “arm, hand”)

    = section "Вмес-" do
      %p The prefix вмес- means “between” or “among”, often corresponding to English inter-.
      %p Examples:
      %ul
        %li #{t "вмеснародне", "vmesnaródne"} “international” (← #{t "народе", "naróde"} “nation”)
        %li #{t "вмессужѣдне", "vmessuźě́dne"} “communal” (← #{t "cужѣде", "suźě́de"} “neighbor”)
        %li #{t "вмесоблостина", "vmesoblóstina"} “interregional highway” (← #{t "облости", "óblosti"} “region”)

    = section "Во-" do
      %p The prefix во- means “in”, “into”, or “inside”, corresponding with certain functions of English in-, as well as most functions of intra-. Before a stem beginning with a vowel, it will reduce to simply #{t "в-", "v-"}.
      %p Examples:
      %ul
        %li #{t "воидрове", "vojidróve"} “intranuclear” (← #{t "идро", "idró"} “nucleus”)
        %li #{t "вовенне", "vovénne"} “intravenous” (← #{t "вена", "véna"} “vein”)
        %li #{t "вовозе", "vóvoze"} “import” (← #{t "вожити", "vóźiti"} “transport”)

    = section "Вонѣ-" do
      %p The basic sense of вонѣ- is “outside”, much like English “extra-”. Befores stems beginning with a vowel, it reduces to #{t "вон-", "von-"}.
      %p Examples:
      %ul
        %li #{t "вонѣклѣсцене", "voněklě́scene"} “extracellular” (← #{t "клѣска", "klě́ska"} “cell”)
        %li #{t "вонѣкрайске", "voněkráiske"} “foreign” (← #{t "крае", "kráie"} “boundary”)

    = section "До-" do
      %p The prefix до- means “before” or “up to”, and corresponds to certain senses of English pre-. Formerly, it could only be used with adjectives, with #{t "пред-", "pred-"} filling in the same role for nouns; nowadays, however, до- is frequently used with both nouns and adjectives, and forms with пред- are gradually disappearing.
      %p Examples:
      %ul
        %li #{t "доисторицеске", "dojistoríceske"} “prehistoric” (← #{t "исторя", "istória"} “history”)
        %li #{t "довоенне", "dovoiénne"} “prewar, antebellum” (← #{t "война", "voiná"} “war”)
        %li #{t "доплоне", "doplóne"} “full to the brim” (← #{t "плоне", "plóne"} “full”)
        %li #{t "дожитенне", "doźítenne"} “lifelong” (← #{t "житени", "źíteni"} “life”)

    = section "За-" do
      %p За- means “after” or “beyond”/”behind”, in both spatial and temporal senses. This can be metaphorically extended to mean a sudden appearance. The first sense only corresponds to English post-; the others do not have a close equivalent.
      %p Examples:
      %ul
        %li #{t "загорне", "zagórne"} “beyond the mountains” (← #{t "гора", "góra"} “mountain”)
        %li #{t "завоенне", "zavoiénne"} “postwar” (← #{t "война", "voiná"} “war”)
        %li #{t "захоте", "záhote"} “desire, craving” (← #{t "хотѣти", "hótěti"} “want”)

    = section "Кољ-" do
      %p The prefix кољ- means “around” or “surrounding”, corresponding  very closely to English circum- or peri-. For the most part it is not used in native coinages, but rather only in calques of scientific or technical terms from other languages, and only forms adjectives. It has the variant form #{t "кол-", "kol-"} before a stem beginning with a front vowel or /j/.
      %p Examples:
      %ul
        %li #{t "кољжемне", "kołźémne"} “circumterrestrial” (← #{t "жемя", "źémia"} “land”)
        %li #{t "кољљунне", "kołłúnne"} “circumlunar” (← #{t "љуна", "łuná"} “moon”)
        %li #{t "кољшердецне", "kołśerdécne"} “pericardial” (← #{t "шерце", "śérce"} “heart”)

    = section "Много-" do
      %p The prefix много- fairly transparently means “many”; semantically, it is similar to English poly- or multi-, but is much more frequent. This is the closest productive equivalent to the -ist- adjective suffix seen in Russian and other Slavic languages, which is disappearing in Novegradian. Before stems beginning in /k/ or /g/, it contracts to #{t "мно-", "mno-"}.
      %p Examples:
      %ul
        %li #{t "многорокове", "mnogorókove"} “many-armed” (← #{t "рока", "róka"} “arm”)
        %li #{t "многорне", "mnogórne"} “mountainous” (← #{t "гора", "góra"} “mountain”)
        %li #{t "многоворне", "mnogovórne"} “talkative” (← #{t "говорити", "govoríti"} “talk”)
        %li #{t "многоедажне", "mnogoiedáźne"} “multistory” (← #{t "едаже", "iedáźe"} “floor, story”)

    = section "На-" do
      %p На- means “on top of”. It has no clear English equivalent.
      %p Examples:
      %ul
        %li #{t "навоцнике", "navócnike"} “contact lens” (← #{t "око", "óko"} “eye”)
        %li #{t "нанижника", "naníźnika"} “book cover” (← #{t "нига", "níga"} “book”)
        %li #{t "настуљне", "nastúłne"} “desktop (#{abbrev 'adj'})” (← #{t "стуље", "stúłe"} “table”)
    
    = section "Над-" do
      %p The prefix над- means “over” or “above”, corresponding to the English prefixes super- and over-. When the stem begins with a plosive consonant, it lenites to #{t "наз-", "naz-"}.
      %p However, this prefix does not have the sense of excess than English over- can have (e.g., “overstep”); nor the sense of “to a great degree” that super- can have (e.g., “superconductivity”), which is handled by the compound пренад-. It covers strictly a literal sense of “over”.
      %p Examples:
      %ul
        %li #{t "наджемне", "nadźémne"} “overhead, elevated” (← #{t "жемя", "źémia"} “land”)
        %li #{t "назкадовуше", "nazkadóvuśe"} “overseer” (← #{t "кадовуше", "kadóvuśe"} “guard”)
        %li #{t "назгуѣздене", "nazguě́zdene"} “heavely (poet.)” (← #{t "гуѣзда", "guě́zda"} “star”)

    = section "Не-" do
      %p The prefix не- performs simple negation, like English un-, non- or a-. With qualitative adjectives, however, it tends to be more of a mild negation, somewhat like English “good” and the mild negative “not good” as opposed to “bad”.
      %p Examples:
      %ul
        %li #{t "невидне", "nevídne"} “invisible” (← #{t "видѣти", "víděti"} “see”)
        %li #{t "невовисяљне", "nevovisiáłne"} “unofficial” (← #{t "овисяљне", "ovisiáłne"} “official”)
        %li #{t "недобре", "nedóbre"} “not good” (← #{t "добре", "dóbre"} “good”)

    = section "Па-" do
      %p The prefix па- does not translate easily into English. When used in a spatial sense, it means “right before” or “immediately by/along”. When used more abstractly, it indicates insufficiency (particularly in the sense of “failure to be sufficient” as opposed to “not yet sufficient”) or more broadly something that is an alternative or secondary, inferior  version of the base stem (though not necessarily with negative connotations). It also often drops stress either onto or toward itself, though this isn’t a universal tendency.
      %p Examples:
      %ul
        %li #{t "павобѣдоке", "pavóbědoke"} “brunch, morning snack” (← #{t "обѣде", "óběde"} “lunch”)
        %li #{t "паежерия", "paiéźerija"} “lakeshore” (← #{t "ежеро", "iéźero"} “lake”)
        %li #{t "павецере", "pavécere"} “twilight” (← #{t "вецере", "vécere"} “evening”)
        %li #{t "пажемка", "paźémka"} “strawberry” (← #{t "жемя", "źémia"} “land”)
        %li #{t "пакусе", "pákuse"} “aftertaste” (← #{t "(во)кусе", "(vó)kuse"} “taste”)
        %li #{t "павука", "pávuka"} “pseudoscience” (← #{t "(на)вука", "(na)vúka"} “science”)

    = section "По-" do
      %p The prefix по-, though very common with verbs and deverbals, is not very common with other nouns and adjectives. It most commonly is used to mean “along” various geographical features. It also has very limited use in the temporal/benefactive sense “for the occasion of”/”upon”.
      %p Examples:
      %ul
        %li #{t "побрѣжне", "pobrě́źne"} “coastal” (← #{t "брѣге", "brě́ge"} “beach”)
        %li #{t "Поневия", "Ponevijá"} “region around the Nevá River” (← #{t "Нева", "Nevá"} “Nevá River”)
        %li #{t "посмортене", "posmórtene"} “upon one’s death”<sup>5</sup> (← #{t "сморти", "smórti"} “death”)

    = section "Под-" do
      %p The prefix под- means “under”, both physically and metaphorically. It also often indicates some sort of alternate to the base stem. Before stems beginning with a plosive, it lenites to #{t "поз-", "poz-"}.
      %p Examples:
      %ul
        %li #{t "подводне", "podvódne"} “underwater” (← #{t "вода", "vóda"} “water”)
        %li #{t "подюданьеве", "podiudánjeve"} “below freezing” (← #{t "юданье", "iudánje"} “freezing”)
        %li #{t "подходе", "pódhode"} “back entrance” (← #{t "ходити", "hóditi"} “go, walk”)
        %li #{t "подиѣзде", "pódiězde"} “back route” (← #{t "ѣздити", "iě́zditi"} “go by vehicle”)

    = section "Пра-" do
      %p The prefix пра- means “preceeding” or “ancestral”, and corresponds very closely to English proto- or, in the context of people, great-. Other than this last sense, it is generally a technical term. The prefix also tends to be stressed equally or nearly equally as much as the stem; for this reason, it was for a long time written hyphenated, though doing so is generally considered dated nowadays.
      %p Examples:
      %ul
        %li #{t "прагуѣзда", "práguě́zda"} “proto-star” (← #{t "гуѣзда", "guě́zda"} “star”)
        %li #{t "прагерманеске", "prágermáneske"} “proto-Germanic” (← #{t "германеске", "germáneske"} “German”)
        %li #{t "прадѣда", "prádě́da"} “great grandfather” (← #{t "дѣда", "dě́da"} “grandfather”)

    = section "Пре-" do
      %p With noun and adjective bases, пре- means “across”. This corresponds most closely with English trans-.
      %p Examples:
      %ul
        %li #{t "прешибиреске", "preśibíreske"} “trans-Siberian” (← #{t "Шибире", "Śibíre"} “Siberia”)
        %li #{t "преятлантицеске", "preiatlantíceske"} “trans-Atlantic” (← #{t "атлантицеске", "atlantíceske"} “Atlantic”)

    = section "Пред-" do
      %p The prefix пред- means “before” when forming nouns. It is falling out of use (except on deverbals) as nouns formed with до- have been gaining acceptance. For example, the only acceptable form for “prehistory” was once #{t "предисторя", "predistória"}, but now the form #{t "доисторя", "dojistória"} is far more common.
    
    = section "При-" do
      %p The prefix при- means, roughly, “adjoining”, “close”, or “toward”. It does not have a close English equivalent, although ad- approximates the first sense. However, при- is much more productive in Novegradian than ad- is in English.
      %p Examples:
      %ul
        %li #{t "примореске", "primóreske"} “maritime” (← #{t "море", "móre"} “sea”)
        %li #{t "притоке", "prítoke"} “tributary [river]” (← #{t "токе", "tóke"} “flow”)
        %li #{t "притољке", "prítołke"} “aftershock” (← #{t "тољке", "tółke"} “tremor”)

    = section "Проти-" do
      %p The prefix проти- means “against”, and behaves much like English anti- or sometimes counter-. Before stems beginning with a vowel, it becomes #{t "против-", "protiv-"}.
      %p Examples:
      %ul
        %li #{t "противирусне", "protivírusne"} “antiviral” (← #{t "вирусе", "víruse"} “virus”)
        %li #{t "протирѣѕия", "protirě́dzija"} “contradiction” (← #{t "рѣѕити", "rědzíti"} “say”)
        %li #{t "противоздушне", "protivozdúśne"} “anti-aircraft” (← #{t "воздушне", "vozdúśne"} “aerial”)

    = section "Со-" do
      %p The prefix со- means “with” or “together”, corresponding to English co- or con-.
      %p Examples:
      %ul
        %li #{t "соврѣменне", "sovrě́menne"} “modern” (← #{t "врѣмено", "vrě́meno"} “time”)
        %li #{t "согуѣздия", "soguědzijá"} “constellation” (← #{t "гуѣзда", "guě́zda"} “star”)
        %li #{t "сотоке", "sótoke"} “confluence” (← #{t "токе", "tóke"} “flow”)

    = section "Compound Prefixes" do
      %p Novegradian also employs three compound substantive prefixes, formed from two of the previously-discussed unary prefixes: #{t "пренад-", "prenad-"}, #{t "недо-", "nedo-"}, and #{t "напроти-", "naproti-"}.
      %p Пренад- corresponds strongly to English super- when used in the sense of “to a great extent”: #{t "преназпроводимости", "prenazprovodímosti"} “superconductivity” (← #{t "проводимости", "provodímosti"} “conductivity”).
      %p Недо- marks insufficiency like па-; however, while па- suggests failure to be sufficient, недо- is more neutral, often signifying that something simply is not yet sufficient. Compare, for instance, #{t "паросуие", "párosuije"} “underdevelopment” (suggesting mismanagement) versus #{t "недоросуие", "nedorosuíje"} “underdevelopment” (suggesting the process of development has only just begun).
      %p Напроти- denotes opposition or rivalry, and is often used to calque English counter-: #{t "напротиреволуця", "nàprotirevolúcia"} “counterrevolution” (← #{t "револуця", "revolúcia"} “revolution”).

    = section "Notes on Formation" do
      %p Whenever a prefix that must end in a vowel is added to a base that begins with a vowel, a prothetic consonant must be added to prevent hiatus. This is entirely dependent on the second vowel. If it is /a e i æ/, the consonant is /j/. If it is /o u ɨ/, the consonant is /β/. In the case of /e i æ u/, there is no visible orthographic change.
      %p When a prefix is added to a root that has undergone the historical TorT or TolT sound change (thus having a modern Novegradian form CraC or ClaC, where “C” represents any consonant), the /a/ is shifted to /o/: #{t "граде", "gráde"} “city” → #{t "пригроде", "prígrode"} “suburb”.
      %p There are two other prefixes that appear in many common nouns, though are no longer productive: #{t "су-/са-", "su-/sa-"} and #{t "о-/об-", "o-/ob-"}. The former derives from Proto-Slavic *sǫ-, so the vowel depends on the dominant stress pattern. It generally indicates some sort of connection, close relationship, or accompaniment: #{t "самраке", "sámrake"} “twilight” (from #{t "мраке", "mráke"} “darkness, gloom”), #{t "сурва", "survá"} “blizzard” (from #{t "ровати", "rováti"} “tear up”), #{t "сутма", "sutmá"} “shadow” (from #{t "тема", "temá"} “darkness”), #{t "сужѣде", "suźě́de"} “neighbor” (from #{t "шѣдѣти", "śědě́ti"} “sit”). The latter (basically *ob-, but frequently reducing to just *o-) means “around”. When it is prefixed to a word beginning in /β/, the /β/ always drops: #{t "власти", "vlásti"} “authority, rule” → #{t "облости", "óblosti"} “region, province”. All of these words have largely been dissociated from their original bases.
      %p When a numeral is prefixed to a noun or adjective, it appears in its genitive form minus any final consonants: #{t "довуногате", "dovunogáte"} “bipedal, two-legged”. If the numeral does not decline, it is simply added as-is: #{t "столѣтия", "stolětijá"} “century, centennial”<sup>6</sup>. The numeral “one” always prefixes as an adjective with a neutral <i>-o-</i> ‘linking morpheme’  (i.e., as #{t "едно-", "iedno-"}). The same rules apply to the numeral #{t "пољ", "pół"} “half”, which prefixed as the genitive #{t "пољу-", "połu-"}.

  = section "Place Names" do
    %p There are five prefixes commonly used to form region names, all based on a more specific geographic term. All region names formed this way must take the collective suffix #{t "-ия", "-ija"}, which triggers palatalization of velar consonants only.
    %p The prefix #{t "по-", "po-"} with a place name means “region along”. It is particularly common with river names, but can also be used with other generic geographic features that are linear, such as “road” or “railroad”. The prefix #{t "па-", "pa-"} is similar, but expresses a greater immediacy.
    - headers = [ "Word", "Meaning", :arrow, "Region Name", "Meaning" ]
    - words = [ [ { :cyr => "Вољга", :lat => "Vółga" },
                  "Volga River",
                  :arrow,
                  [ { :cyr => "Повољжия", :lat => "Povółźija" }, { :cyr => "Павољжия", :lat => "Pávołźija" } ],
                  "Volga region<br><br>Volga riverside" ],
                [ { :cyr => "Нева", :lat => "Nevá" },
                  "Nevá River",
                  :arrow,
                  [ { :cyr => "Поневия", :Lat => "Ponévija" }, { :cyr => "Паневия", :lat => "Pánevija" } ],
                  "Nevá region<br><br>Nevá riverside" ],
                [ { :cyr => "далница", :lat => "dálnica" },
                  "highway",
                  :arrow,
                  { :cyr => "падалниция", :lat => "pádalnicija" },
                  "highway shoulder, roadside" ] ]
    = render 'derivation_table', :headers => headers, :words => words
    %p The prefix #{t "при-", "pri-"} does the same, but marks the area along a coastline.
    - words = [ [ { :cyr => "балтицеске", :lat => "baltíceske" },
                  "Baltic (sea)<sup>7</sup>",
                  :arrow,
                  { :cyr => "Прибалтия", :lat => "Pribáltija" },
                  "Baltic states" ],
                [ { :cyr => "ежеро Ладожеское", :lat => "iéźero Ladoźeskóie" },
                  "Lake Ladoga",
                  :arrow,
                  { :cyr => "Приладожия", :lat => "priladóźija" },
                  "Ladoga region" ] ]
    = render 'derivation_table', :headers => headers, :words => words
    %p #{t "Под-", "pod-"} (or #{t "поз-", "poz-"} before plosive consonants) marks the region around a city.
    - words = [ [ { :cyr => "Новеграде", :lat => "Novegráde" },
                  "Novegrad",
                  :arrow,
                  { :cyr => "Подновеградия", :lat => "Podnovegrádija" },
                  "Novegrad region" ],
                [ { :cyr => "Москуа", :lat => "Moskuá" },
                  "Moscow",
                  :arrow,
                  { :cyr => "Подмоскевия", :lat => "Podmoskévija" },
                  "Moscow region" ],
                [ { :cyr => "Лондоне", :lat => "Lóndone" },
                  "London",
                  :arrow,
                  { :cyr => "Подлондония", :lat => "Podlóndonija" },
                  "London region" ] ]
    = render 'derivation_table', :headers => headers, :words => words
    %p #{t "За-", "za-"} is used with names of or terms referring to physical features, most often mountain ranges, to mean “land beyond”, much like trans- may be used in English.
    - words = [ [ { :cyr => "Кауказе", :lat => "Kaukáze" },
                  "Caucasus",
                  :arrow,
                  { :cyr => "Закауказия", :lat => "Zakaukázija" },
                  "Transcaucasia" ],
                [ { :cyr => "влаке", :lat => "vláke" },
                  "portage",
                  :arrow,
                  { :cyr => "Завлация", :lat => "Zavlácija" },
                  "Zavolotia<br><i>(central Novegrad)</i>" ] ]
    = render 'derivation_table', :headers => headers, :words => words
    %p #{t "До-", "do-"} may occasionally be used to mean “land on this side of” (English cis-), but this is rare: #{t "Докауказия", "Dokaukázija"} “Ciscaucasia”.

  = section "Verb Prefixes" do
    %p Verbs share many of the same prefixes nouns and adjectives use, although they function somewhat differently. Verbal prefixes in Novegradian are in many cases roughly equivalent to phrasal verbs in English, allowing a single verb root to spawn a wide variety of related verbs. These prefixes are highly productive, especially for verbs of motion.
    %p The prefixes from which the perfective form of a verb is chosen are the same as the derivational prefixes. Where по- may turn one verb perfective, for another it may be solely derivational.
    %p Note, though, that all verbs created through prefixial derivation are strictly speaking perfective. Most such verbs then back-derive an imperfective form using the suffix #{t "-ов-/-ав-", "-ov-/-av-"}: #{t "дати", "dáti"} (#{abbrev 'impf'}) → #{t "содати", "sodáti"} (#{abbrev 'pf'}); #{t "предати", "predáti"} (#{abbrev 'pf'}) → #{t "предавати", "predaváti"} (#{abbrev 'impf'}). Almost all back-derived imperfectives are first conjugation; the one exception is -давати, which is third.
    %p A smaller set of verbs, all second conjugation, derive imperfective forms by shifting directly to the first conjugation without the aid of an overt suffix. If the root-final consonant can undergo palatalization, it will; in other words, /s(ʲ) z(ʲ) t d n p b m β/ → /ç ʝ c ɟ ɲ pl bl ml wl/, with some allowances for stress-related voicing. Examples: #{t "вуишити", "vuíśiti"} “raise” → #{t "вуиғьати", "vuiğjáti"}, #{t "прицинити", "priciníti"} “cause” → #{t "прициньати", "pricinjáti"}, #{t "соправити", "sopráviti"} → #{t "сопраулати", "sopráulati"}. In speech, however, these types of imperfectives are becoming increasingly uncommon.

    = section "Без-" do
      %p The prefix без- marks removal. Semantically, it is similar to English dis-, although in practice there is a rather low correspondence between the two. It becomes #{t "бес-", "bes-"} before voiceless consonants. While it does occasionally occur on its own, it is by far more common in the compound form #{t "обез-", "obez-"}, where the <i>о-</i> reinforces the transformative sense of без-. Most of the verbs that take plain без- take обез- in the perfective.
      %p Examples:
      %ul
        %li #{t "безвѣрити", "bezvě́riti"} “cause smby to lose faith in” (← #{t "вѣрити", "vě́riti"} “believe”)
        %li #{t "безоружити", "bezoruźíti"} “disarm” (← #{t "оружия", "orúźija"} “weaponry”)
        %li #{t "бесстрашити", "besstráśiti"} “insure” (← #{t "страшити", "stráśiti"} “frighten”)

    = section "Во-" do
      %p The prefix во- marks some sort of movement or action into something else, and is comparable to English in-. It becomes #{t "в-", "v-"} before stems beginning with a vowel, and occasionally in other situations as well (see section 10.3.3.19).
      %p Examples:
      %ul
        %li #{t "вокражити", "vokráźiti"} “encircle” (← #{t "краге", "kráge"} “circle”)
        %li #{t "войсти", "vóisti"} “walk in[to]” (← #{t "исти", "ísti"} “go, walk”)
        %li #{t "влѣти", "vlě́ti"} “instil” (← #{t "лѣти", "lě́ti"} “pour”)
      
    = section "Вуи-" do
      %p The basic meaning of the prefix вуи- is “out of”, and it is the opposite of во-. However, metaphorical extensions of this meaning are very common; for example, вуи- may also refer to any sort of distribution from one source to many, revelations/sharing of information, or the fulfilment of a difficult action. This wide array of meanings makes it hard to compare to any English constructions; the closest analogy is probably to be found in phrasal verbs with “out”.
      %p Examples:
      %ul
        %li #{t "вуийсти", "vuíjsti"} “exit, walk out” (← #{t "исти", "ísti"} “go, walk”)
        %li #{t "вуижити", "vuiźíti"} “survive, live out” (← #{t "жити", "źíti"} “live”)
        %li #{t "вуикриѕати", "vuikridzáti"} “shout out” (← #{t "криѕати", "kridzáti"} “shout”)
        %li #{t "вуидати", "vuidáti"} “issue, give out” (← #{t "дати", "dáti"} “give”)
        %li #{t "вуилѣти", "vuilě́ti"} “pour out, empty” (← #{t "лѣти", "lě́ti"} “pour”)
        %li #{t "вуипуидати", "vuipuidáti"} “demand” (← #{t "пуидати", "puidáti"} “ask”)
        %li #{t "вуитуорити", "vuituóriti"} “produce, manufacture” (← #{t "туорити", "tuoríti"} “create”)
        %li #{t "вуибрати", "vuibráti"} “choose, pick out” (← #{t "брати", "bráti"} “take, bring”)

    = section "До-" do
      %p The prefix до- means “up to/reaching” or “additional”.
      %p Examples:
      %ul
        %li #{t "доцидати", "docidáti"} “read up to” (← #{t "цидати", "cidáti"} “read”)
        %li #{t "доѣсати", "doiě́sati"} “go up to/as far as [a place]” (← #{t "ѣсати", "iě́sati"} “go by vehicle”)
        %li #{t "догрѣти", "dogrě́ti"} “heat up [to]” (← #{t "грѣти", "grě́ti"} “heat”)
        %li #{t "довѣсти", "dově́sti"} “understand” (← #{t "вѣсти", "vě́sti"} “know”)
        %li #{t "додати", "dodáti"} “add, tack onto” (← #{t "дати", "dáti"} “give”)
      %p While the sense of “additional” is undeniably derivational, many believe the former sense of “up to/reaching” has become grammaticalized. For example, the prefix до- is virtually required on the verb whenever the preposition до “up to” is present in the same sentence, and this can be done freely with any verb. This function is sometimes known as the “telic prefix”, which will be discussed further in section 11.15.

    = section "За-" do
      %p The prefix за- is hard to describe. It covers a wide array of meanings that are often contradictory, and the exact role it plays in the historical derivation of many verbs is no longer clear. This is part of why за- has become one of the most common simple perfectivizing suffixes with no lexical content of its own. The four most common senses, however, are: inchoateness/beginning an action (and by extension causatives in general); movement or action behind something; some sort of exchange or action that occurs with clear benefit to the subject; and an action done quickly, often viewed as not being quite as thorough as the base action it was derived from. In addition, with verbs of motion, it indicates performing an action while in the process of doing something else (e.g., “stop by [while on the way to...]”, “drop off [while on the way to...]”, etc.).
      %p Examples:
      %ul
        %li #{t "зайсти", "záisti"} “stop by, drop by” (← #{t "исти", "ísti"} “go, walk”)
        %li #{t "зашинати", "zaśináti"} “fall asleep” (← #{t "спати", "spáti"} “sleep”)
        %li #{t "затемнѣти", "zatemně́ti"} “darken suddenly” (← #{t "темнѣти", "temně́ti"} “become dark”)
        %li #{t "забоити", "zabójiti"} “conquer, take in battle” (← #{t "бое", "bóie"} “battle”)
        %li #{t "закрити", "zakríti"} “veil, screen” (← #{t "крити", "kríti"} “cover”)
        %li #{t "запизати", "zapizáti"} “note” (← #{t "пизати", "pizáti"} “write”)
        %li #{t "залежити", "zaleźíti"} “establish” (← #{t "лежити", "leźiti"} “lie [down]”)
        %li #{t "забуити", "zabuíti"} “forget” (← #{t "буити", "buíti"} “be”)

    = section "На-" do
      %p The prefix на- generally indicates action on or onto something. When in the middle voice, it may indicate an action completed to exhaustion.
      %p Examples:
      %ul
        %li #{t "найсти", "náisti"} “come upon, find” (← #{t "исти", "ísti"} “go, walk”)
        %li #{t "наѣстиш", "naiě́stiś"} “eat one’s fill” (← #{t "ѣсти", "iě́sti"} “eat”)
        %li #{t "надумати", "nadúmati"} “think over” (← #{t "думати", "dúmati"} “ponder”)
        %li #{t "наработатиш", "narabótatiś"} “have done a lot of work” (← #{t "работати", "rabótati"} “work”)
        %li #{t "настубати", "nastubáti"} “step on, tread on” (← #{t "стубати", "stubáti"} “step”)

    = section "Над-" do
      %p The prefix над- means “over”. Before bases beginning with plosives, it lenites to #{t "наз-", "naz-"}.
      %p Examples:
      %ul
        %li #{t "наздати", "nazdáti"} “increase” (← #{t "дати", "dáti"} “give”)
        %li #{t "назпизати", "nazpizáti"} “write over, superscribe” (← #{t "пизати", "pizáti"} “write”)
        %li #{t "надсуѣдати", "nadsuědáti"} “suggest as an alternative” (← #{t "суѣдати", "suědáti"} “suggest”)
        %li #{t "назтемнѣти", "naztemně́ti"} “eclipse, overshadow” (← #{t "темнѣти", "temně́ti"} “become dark”)

    = section "О-" do
      %p The prefix о- is the result of the merger of two older prefixes. One marked simple transformations, and so is very common with deadjectival and denominal bases, as well as “around” or “about”. The other suggests movement away from something.
      %p Examples:
      %ul
        %li #{t "обрати", "obráti"} “take away” (← #{t "брати", "bráti"} “bring, take”)
        %li #{t "одужити", "oduźíti"} “kill (poet.)” (← #{t "духе", "dúhe"} “breath”)
        %li #{t "овелицити", "ovelíciti"} “increase, enlarge” (← #{t "велике", "velíke"} “great”)
        %li #{t "овратити", "ovrátiti"} “turn, rotate” (← #{t "вратити", "vrátiti"} “return, turn back”)
        %li #{t "ознати", "oznáti"} “acknowledge” (← #{t "знати", "znáti"} “recognize”)
        %li #{t "опизати", "opizáti"} “describe” (← #{t "пизати", "pizáti"} “write”)
        %li #{t "ойсти", "óisti"} “leave” (← #{t "исти", "ísti"} “go, walk”)

    = section "От-" do
      %p The prefix от-, which becomes ос- before bases beginning with a plosive, indicates movement away, much like о-. However, о- suggests movement out of sight, while от- suggests movement just a short distance away, while remaining in sight<sup>8</sup>. It also frequently indicates physical removal (and thus is more literal than без-), a mistake in performing an action, or the undoing or reciprocation of an action performed by another party.
      %p Examples:
      %ul
        %li #{t "осдати", "osdáti"} “answer, respond” (← #{t "дати", "dáti"} “give”)
        %li #{t "отѣйграти", "otěigráti"} “win back” (← #{t "еграти", "iegráti"} “play”)
        %li #{t "осцидати", "oscidáti"} “misread” (← #{t "цидати", "cidáti"} “read”)
        %li #{t "отлежити", "otleźíti"} “set aside” (← #{t "лежити", "leźíti"} “lie down”)
        %li #{t "отношити", "otnóśiti"} “carry off, deliver” (← #{t "ношити", "nóśiti"} “carry”)
        %li #{t "отрѣзати", "otrězáti"} “cut off [from]” (← #{t "рѣзати", "rězáti"} “cut”)

    = section "Па-" do
      %p The prefix па- has a variety of different meanings. It originally spread to verbs via denominals; in early Common Slavic the nominal prefix па- was more or less considered a variant of по-. In these original verbs derived from nouns, the function of па- can be very opaque. However, over time it developed a sense of insufficiency or absence in nouns (see section 10.3.1.12), and this sense spread to verbs. As a result, most productive use of the verbal prefix па- nowadays indicates insufficiency. There is a strong tendency to stress the prefix.
      %p Examples:
      %ul
        %li #{t "пагубити", "págubiti"} “ruin” (← #{t "губити", "gubíti"} “destroy”)
        %li #{t "пажити", "páźiti"} “pasture” (← #{t "жити", "źíti"} “live”)
        %li #{t "пакормити", "pákormiti"} “underfeed” (← #{t "кормити", "kórmiti"} “feed”)

    = section "По-" do
      %p By far the most common meaning of по- is “for a while”; that is, it indicates durative aspect. This is a highly productive process, as it can be applied to virtually any verb. A secondary sense, far less common, is as an inchoative.
      %p Examples:
      %ul
        %li #{t "поговорити", "pogovoríti"} “talk for a bit” (← #{t "говорити", "govoríti"} “talk”)
        %li #{t "побуити", "pobuíti"} “stay for some time” (← #{t "буити", "buíti"} “be”)
        %li #{t "полубити", "polubíti"} “fall in love” (← #{t "лубити", "lubíti"} “love”)

    = section "Под-" do
      %p The basic meaning of под- is “under” or “from under”. However, it has acquired a number of metaphorical extensions of this original sense. It can indicate approach to another person (not an object), or it can weaken the sense of a verb. It can also be used as a generic prefix of politeness when attached to verbs of human interaction. Before bases beginning with a plosive, the prefix becomes #{t "поз-", "poz-"}.
      %p Examples:
      %ul
        %li #{t "позпизати", "pozpizáti"} “sign” (← #{t "пизати", "pizáti"} “write”)
        %li #{t "подмотрѣти", "podmótrěti"} “spy on” (← #{t "мотрѣти", "mótrěti"} “watch”)
        %li #{t "подѣскоцити", "poděskóciti"} “jump out” (← #{t "скоцити", "skóciti"} “jump”)
        %li #{t "подрѣѕити", "podrědzíti"} “say [please]” (← #{t "рѣѕити", "rědzíti"} “say”)
        %li #{t "подѣгрѣти", "poděgrě́ti"} “warm up a little bit” (← #{t "грѣти", "grě́ti"} “heat up”)
        %li #{t "подѣйсти", "póděisti"} “walk up to” (← #{t "исти", "ísti"} “go, walk”)
        %li #{t "подсушити", "podsúśiti"} “dry a little” (← #{t "сушити", "súśiti"} “dry”)

    = section "Пре-" do
      %p The prefix пре- has five primary senses. The original is physical action across something. It can also indicate repetition, thoroughness, reciprocation, and excess.
      %p Examples:
      %ul
        %li #{t "предумати", "predúmati"} “think over, ponder” (← #{t "думати", "dúmati"} “muse”)
        %li #{t "предати", "predáti"} “transmit, broadcast” (← #{t "дати", "dáti"} “give”)
        %li #{t "премирити", "premíriti"} “cease fire” (← #{t "мире", "míre"} “peace”)
        %li #{t "преговорити", "pregovoríti"} “hold talks” (← #{t "говорити", "govoríti"} “talk”)
        %li #{t "премотрѣти", "premótrěti"} “revise, reconsider” (← #{t "мотрѣти", "mótrěti"} “watch”)
        %li #{t "премѣстити", "preměstíti"} “relocate, move” (← #{t "мѣсто", "mě́sto"} “place”)
        %li #{t "препизати", "prepizáti"} “rewrite” (← #{t "пизати", "pizáti"} “write”)
        %li #{t "препизатиш", "prepizátiś"} “correspond, write one another” (← #{t "пизати", "pizáti"} “write”)
        %li #{t "престубити", "prestubíti"} “infringe, violate” (← #{t "стубати", "stubáti"} “step” [i.e., overstep])
        %li #{t "прегрѣти", "pregrě́ti"} “overheat” (← #{t "грѣти", "grě́ti"} “heat up”)

    = section "Пред-" do
      %p The prefix пред- means “before” or “in front”. It lenites to #{t "през-", "prez-"} before bases beginning with a plosive.
      %p Examples:
      %ul
        %li #{t "предвидѣти", "predvíděti"} “foresee” (← #{t "видѣти", "víděti"} “see”)
        %li #{t "предсудити", "predsudíti"} “prejudge” (← #{t "судити", "sudíti"} “judge”)
        %li #{t "предрѣѕити", "predrědzíti"} “foretell, predict” (← #{t "рѣѕити", "rědzíti"} “say”)
    
    = section "При-" do
      %p The prefix при- conveys a variety of meanings all denoting some sort of closeness. It often indicates motion toward, arrival, preparation, invitation, appearance of emotions or ideas, and attentiveness.
      %p Examples:
      %ul
        %li #{t "прийсти", "príjsti"} “arrive, approach” (← #{t "исти", "ísti"} “go, walk”)
        %li #{t "применѣти", "primeně́ti"} “remember, recall” (← #{t "менѣти", "meně́ti"} “seem, suppose”)
        %li #{t "придумати", "pridúmati"} “think up” (← #{t "думати", "dúmati"} “muse”)
        %li #{t "привезати", "privezáti"} “tie to” (← #{t "везати", "vezáti"} “tie”)
        %li #{t "призуати", "prizuáti"} “invite” (← #{t "зуати", "zuáti"} “call”)
        %li #{t "припозобити", "pripozóbiti"} “adjust for, adapt to” (← #{t "позоба", "pozóba"} “means, method”)
        %li #{t "прислухѣти", "prislúhěti"} “listen attentively” (← #{t "слухѣти", "slúhěti"} “listen”)
        %li #{t "прийграти", "prijgráti"} “join a game” (← #{t "еграти", "iegráti"} “play”)

    = section "Про-" do
      %p The prefix про- primarily indicates motion through or past something. In addition, it may indicate a somewhat haphazard or not entirely focused action, especially one that results in some sort of error or mistake.
      %p Examples:
      %ul
        %li #{t "пройсти", "próisti"} “go through; go past” (← #{t "исти", "ísti"} “go, walk”)
        %li #{t "пропизати", "propizáti"} “jot down” (←  #{t "пизати", "pizáti"} “write”)
        %li #{t "прослухѣти", "proslúhěti"} “not catch someone’s words” (← #{t "слухѣти", "slúhěti"} “listen”)
        %li #{t "прожити", "proźíti"} “live through” (← #{t "жити", "źíti"} “live”)
        %li #{t "пролѣти", "prolě́ti"} “spill” (← #{t "лѣти", "lě́ti"} “pour”)
    
    = section "Роз-" do
      %p The prefix роз- indicates separation or distribution. It may also indicate an action is completely out of control. Before bases beginning with an unvoiced consonant, it becomes <i>ros-</i>.
      %p Examples:
      %ul
        %li #{t "роздати", "rozdáti"} “distribute” (← #{t "дати", "dáti"} “give”)
        %li #{t "розлѣти", "rozlě́ti"} “flood” (← #{t "лѣти", "lě́ti"} “pour”)
        %li #{t "розиѣсти", "roziě́sti"} “erode, eat away at” (← #{t "ѣсти", "iě́sti"} “eat”)
        %li #{t "розбрати", "rozbráti"} “take apart, examine” (← #{t "брати", "bráti"} “bring, take”)
        %li #{t "росуити", "rosuíti"} “unwind, evolve” (← #{t "вити", "víti"} “twist”)
        %li #{t "розѣйсти", "rózěisti"} “part ways” (← #{t "исти", "ísti"} “go, walk”)

    = section "Со-" do
      %p The prefix со- indicates joining many things together (the opposite of роз-), getting off of or down from something (and occasionally removal), or an exhaustive action.
      %p Examples:
      %ul
        %li #{t "собрати", "sobráti"} “gather” (← #{t "брати", "bráti"} “bring, take”)
        %li #{t "сойсти", "sóisti"} “get off” (← #{t "исти", "ísti"} “go, walk”)
        %li #{t "снести", "snésti"} “bring down” (← #{t "нести", "nésti"} “carry”)
        %li #{t "сократити", "sokrátiti"} “cut short” (← #{t "кратити", "krátiti"} “shorten”)
        %li #{t "сожитиш", "soźítiś"} “get accustomed to” (← #{t "жити", "źíti"} “live”)
        %li #{t "совинити", "soviníti"} “forgive, pardon” (← #{t "винити", "viníti"} “blame”)
        %li #{t "согорѣти", "sogorě́ti"} “burn out, go out” (← #{t "горѣти", "gorě́ti"} “burn, glow”)
    
    = section "Notes on Formation" do
      %p The interaction of the prefixes #{t "в(о)-", "v(o)-"} and #{t "с(о)-", "s(o)-"} with the verb root can be somewhat complex at times. Generally, the preferred prefixes are the vocalic forms во- and со-. However, before /l/ (and usually before /m n/, and irregularly before /r/), the vowel will drop: во + ливати → #{t "вливати", "vliváti"} “pour in, instil”. Before /β/, the realization depends on stress. If the first syllable of the verb root is unstressed, then the vocalic prefixes are used: со + винити → #{t "совинити", "soviníti"} “pardon”. If the first syllable of the verb root is stressed, then the vowel is dropped and the /β/ elides to /w/: со + вити → #{t "суити", "suíti"} “twist”.
      %p However, when deverbalized, the vowel may reappear even though it is absent in the verb: #{t "вложити", "vloźíti"} “invest” → #{t "вологе", "vóloge"} “investment”. Sometimes both vowelless and vowelled derivatives exist with different semantics.
      %p With the exception of в(о)- and с(о)-, the standard epenthetic vowel used with verbal prefixes is -ѣ-. This occurs, for instance, when a prefix ending with a consonant is applied to a base that begins with a consonant cluster. There are also certain verb stems beginning with /i/ or /(j)e/ that reduce to /j/ when any prefix is added, which will then require this additional -ѣ-: #{t "исти", "ísti"} “go, walk” → ##{t "подѣйсти", "póděisti"} “walk up to”.

= section "Compounds" do
  %p Novegradian has two kinds of compounds—linked and unlinked, referring to whether or not there is a ‘linking morpheme’. Both are very common, although the ‘linked’ form is used more often in recent constructs.

  = section "Unlinked Compounds" do
    %p Unlinked compounds for the most part are limited to adverbs and conjunctions. Nouns and adjectives are rarely formed with unlinked compounds, with the exception of compounds incorporating a numeral as the first element.
    %p Taking a number in its genitive form and attaching it to an adjective or noun is a common method of substantive creation: #{t "довуногате", "dòvunogáte"} “bipedal”, #{t "дешитанлико", "dèśitángliko"} “decagon”, #{t "полувѣке", "pòluvě́ke"} “half-century”.
    %p Many modern adverbs come from historical compounds, where what was originally a phrase became fused into a single unit:
    %ul
      %li #{t "вноу", "vnóu"} “again” ← во “in” + нов(е) “new”
      %li #{t "воврехѣ", "vovréhě"} “[located] above” ← во “in” + врехѣ “top (#{abbrev 'loc'})”
      %li #{t "вонизѣ", "vonízě"} “[located] below” ← во “in” + низѣ “bottom (#{abbrev 'loc'})”
      %li #{t "слѣва", "slě́va"} “from the left” ← со “from” + лѣва “left (#{abbrev 'gen'})”
      %li #{t "коправом", "koprávom"} “toward the right” ← ко “toward” + правом “right (#{abbrev 'datins'})”
      %li #{t "хоиж", "hójiź"} “who (#{abbrev 'emph'})” ← хой “who” + же (an emphatic particle)
      %li #{t "шеден", "śedén"} “today” ← ше “this” + ден “day (#{abbrev 'acc'})”
      %li #{t "занок", "zánok"} ← за “behind” + нокьи “night”
      %li #{t "вецераш", "véceraś"} “yesterday” ← вецера “evening (#{abbrev 'gen'})” + ш(ево) “this”

  = section "Linked Compounds" do
    %p Linked compounds feature a fill vowel, most commonly /o/, separating the two components of the compound. If the second element begins with a vowel, the fill vowel may be dropped; this is optional, but generally preferred.
    - headers = [ "Word 1", "Word 2", :arrow, "Compound" ]
    - words = [ [ "#{t "рока", "róka"}<br>“hand”",
                  "#{t "пизанье", "pizánje"}<br>“writing”",
                  :arrow,
                  "#{t "рокопизанье", "ròkopizánje"}<br>handwriting" ],
                [ "#{t "шѣверне", "śě́verne"}<br>“northern”",
                  "#{t "Америка", "Amérika"}<br>“America”",
                  :arrow,
                  "#{t "Шѣверн(о)америка", "Śěvern(o)amérika"}<br>“North America”" ] ]
    = render 'derivation_table', :headers => headers, :words => words
    %p When the second element is a verb, but the compound itself is not, the verb will appear as just the root alone.
    - words = [ [ "#{t "жемя", "źémia"}<br>“land”",
                  "#{t "вѣсти", "vě́sti"}<br>“know”",
                  :arrow,
                  "#{t "жемловѣде", "źemlově́de"}<br>“geologist”" ],
                [ "#{t "вода", "vóda"}<br>“water”",
                  "#{t "родити", "rodíti"}<br>“bear”",
                  :arrow,
                  "#{t "водороде", "vodoróde"}<br>“hydrogen”" ],
                [ "#{t "вино", "vinó"}<br>“wine”",
                  "#{t "лубити", "lubíti"}<br>“love”",
                  :arrow,
                  "#{t "винолубе", "vinolúbe"}<br>“wine connoisseur”" ] ]
    = render 'derivation_table', :headers => headers, :words => words

